📈 Russian economy forecast has been improved

IMF has stated that it has increased estimates of Russian economy growth from –2.3% contraction to 0.3% growth in 2023 despite a broad array of Western sanctions.

The IMF attributes this improvement to Russia finding new clients outside the West by redirecting trade from sanctioning to non-sanctioning countries. Activity of Russian defense industrial complex was one of the main contributors for projected growth.

These are good news, as we know that Western forecasts never favor Russia. Last year they forecasted collapse of Russian economy, then they stated that it will not return to growth until second half of 2020s, then it was 2024 and now it has already happened.

It looks like IMF reluctantly acknowledged amazingly quick recovery of Russian economy to add credibility to its other forecasts, such as the one concerning Europe. Yes, you heard it right, they forecast that European economy will grow in 2023. Despite it having far deeper problems than Russia. 

The thing is that Russia had to find customers for its export products, which are in very high demand. This was not really a problem as long as two thirds of the world didn’t join Western sanctions or simply ignored them. 

European problem is different, they need to find resources, especially energy. Amid looming energy crisis and soaring prices that are expected to come this year when Chinese reopening gains momentum, their chances to get a good deal are slim. 

For now, Europe is still living on Russian resources, despite all of their nice words. They are getting them from intermediary countries while some are coming directly from Russia. There is physically no way to replace Russian supplies and maintain European industry competitive, so all growth forecasts are likely to be artificial. 

There is a fundamental flaw in IMF estimations of economic growth. They estimate this growth in US dollars, and it is no longer a stable currency as it once used to be. 

Moreover, the rate of USD and EUR is greatly inflated and as these currencies are slowly but steadily losing relevance for international trade, estimates in these currencies are no longer objective. More objective are estimations based on purchasing power of currency and not on its market rate to USD. 

If we estimate things by purchasing power parity, we’ll see that Russian economy is actually twice stronger than it seems to the West, and so its growth is far better than anyone could guess. For reference, while market exchange rate is around $1 = 70 rubles, purchasing power rate is under 30 rubles per dollar.

Fortunately for Russia, dollar rate has little impact on its economy and influences only foreign trade. As Russia is readjusting its import-export flows, higher dollar rate means that Russia earns more money through export and can afford to import more goods, which translates into lower consumer prices. 

A fun fact, prices on modern notebooks in Russia fell by 25 percent since last October due to competition of parallel import and Chinese manufacturers trying to enter the lucrative Russian market. So, Russia is fine. Can’t say that of Europe.

⬛️ According to recent report in Financial Times, almost 90 percent of surveyed economists expect that energy shortage will trigger eurozone contraction in 2023. 

Experts acknowledge that European economy is already in recession and it will intensify next year even more. High inflation and energy shortage push a strong pressure on EU industry, salary increases are falling short behind inflation, consumer demand falls and this is triggering a chain reaction that will manifest most noticeably in the coming year.

This report greatly contradicts optimistic statements of European politicians, which in fact turn to be quite void. This year Europe managed to reduce its energy consumption by 20 percent. But how was it achieved? Despite widely publicized household energy-saving measures, they account just for a tiny bit of energy consumption. Expensive transition to energy-efficient technologies also helped a tiny bit, but the lion’s share of energy saving is due to reduced consumption by European industry. 

Plants are reducing production, businesses close, companies see lower profits and are looking for ways to cut costs. Facing much higher energy costs and falling demand they are virtually forced to “optimize” labor costs, resulting in even more unemployment, even lower demand and so on.

For many decades European industry was considered innovative and competitive, for many years European income level was considered relatively high as compared to most other countries. We knew that a good part of high income was compensated with high costs of living, but we thought that aside for that best European countries are really demonstrating outstanding competence in running their economies. 

However, it turned out that all of this was just an illusion and the real foundation of European competitiveness was very simple — cheap Russian energy that it was getting from USSR and later Russia. With few exceptions such as Norway that has its own energy resources, the competitiveness of Europe was dependent on Russian energy and it was an incredible level of dependence that nobody could even imagine.

Energy prices impact industry not only directly through the energy it consumes but also indirectly through increased prices on components and higher costs of storage and transportation. Even slight increase in energy prices has multiplicative effect on manufacturing costs of final product. 

Now just think, Europe now pays 2-4 times more for its energy. Consumer sector is subsidized, but subsidies won’t work for industry. Paying billions to subsidize companies and getting back millions in taxes does not sound like a plan. It can work for a short period, but European pockets are not endless and the crisis spiral is already in motion. 

In face of inevitable increase of global demand for energy, the Eurozone sees itself in completely uncompetitive position. The euro bubble will sooner or later burst out, and European authorities can do little to prevent it.

Still, it can be a good sign for Europe as well. When Europe shifts to survival mode, there is a good chance that hardships will finally open the eyes of European people and they will kick out globalist talking heads out and elect new generation politicians out of more reasonable people.
Its inability to sustain its own military and admitted shortfalls of Western arms industry that cannot ramp up production fast enough to make a meaningful impact. Stock reserves are over.

⬛️ Ukrainian energy grid is down, what next? 

Massive Russian strikes over Ukrainian energy grid with missiles and drones have virtually achieved their results. The power grid is down and this seriously hinders mobility of enemy forces, supplies and whatever is left of Ukrainian arms industry.

While Zelensky’s regime is trying to pretend that nothing serious has happened, they have already prohibited citizens talk about blackouts publicly. They pretend that those without electricity are a part of “the unfortunate 1 percent”. That’s their usual math, the one they use to calculate casualties, secure financial aid and so on. 

Kiev rulers are acting as if they have already secured victory, and this makes sense for them — nobody will send money to losers and extracting money from the West is becoming the favorite sport of Zelensky and Co.

They are virtually forcing citizens to stay at cities without stable supply of power, hot water and central heating. They lie because they need to show a nice picture to their sponsors. We have always known that well-being of civilians has zero relevance to Kiev regime, they have already proven it with there endless shelling of Donbass. 

▪️By the way, that shelling still continues — while people in the West were watching FIFA World Cup, Ukrainian artillery have launched a massive strike against civilian hospital in Donetsk that involved casualties. It was just the last of the series of similar strikes against residential buildings, temples, cafes and other civilian infrastructure. 

These strikes have no military sense, there were no military objects or armed forces in the vicinity of impacted areas. In fact, they perfectly fit definition of war crime. Moreover, Ukraine still claims Donetsk to be its territory but it does not have any concerns about people that it wants to return… or not. In fact, it’s common knowledge that Ukraine just wants those rich lands, no people needed. 

▪️The Ukrainian regime enforces “stay home” agenda for several reasons, and the main reason is that if Zelensky allows people to leave, Ukraine will get empty. EU will face another migration crisis while it hasn’t even barely accommodated to the previous one. Several more millions of Ukrainian migrants in EU will inevitably cause an explosion among local people and they will start looking for someone responsible. 

▪️Zelensky is too minor figure to answer for all European problems but his helpers are still around —EU parliament, EU government, leaders of EU countries. All those proponents of “solidarity with Ukraine” who decided that a chance for a victorious war is worth suffering of their people. No way.

So, Ukrainian energy grid is down. Zelensky regime may extend its agony by a couple more weeks with help of Europeans, so Russian pressure has to continue. Next priority targets are air defense, supply lines and fuel facilities. 

▪️The greater is the Russian pressure, the higher is the chance that Zelensky will no longer be able to hide the truth from his sponsors and, more importantly, from his people. If soldiers of Ukrainian armed forces learn more about real situation at home, they may come for Zelensky and the little fuhrer won’t like it.

🔴 Will subsidies save the crumbling EU industry?

EU Parliament has finally noticed the looming economic problems and potential loss of competitiveness of European industry. On Thursday, December 15 they are planning to discuss measures that can be taken to address the dire situation that the EU faces in short-term, mid-term and long-term perspective. 

Sanctions against Russia can indeed be compared to shooting oneself in a leg. While Russia did not really notice their impact, Europe is now facing one of the hardest challenges for its economy in all its history. As energy prices have soared, more and more large European businesses are looking to move their industrial facilities overseas. 

The United States have longed opposed cooperation between Russia and Europe in energy sector. Inexpensive Russian pipeline gas brought European industry incredible competitive advantages that negated disadvantages of high cost of labor and high tax burden. Moreover, it enabled many European industries such as the car industry to successfully compete with American enterprises at foreign markets that the U.S. considers their own playground. 

Now Europe finally got rid of its dependence on “non-democratic” Russian gas, and is no longer dependent on Russia. According to recent revelations of Werner Steinecker, ex-CEO of Austrian Energie AG, EU has signed 20-year LNG supply contracts with the United States based on “take or pay” formula that met such a harsh critics in Europe when it was used by Russia.

This means that European Union will have to pay the United States any “market price” just to meet their basic demands. Costs of energy are already rising and they are not so noticeable by European consumers only because of government subsidies. 

▪️Moreover, U.S. subsidies of their own industry may deal the last stroke to competitiveness of Europe although their long-term impact on U.S. economy is also controversial. European countries have little to do in response except for taking similar measures. 

France has proposed unrestricted subsidies to European industrial enterprises and this proposal is supported by many other EU countries with notable exception of Scandinavia that suffers less from the energy crisis. 

▪️The problem with industrial subsidies is that while they can give short-term boost to industry, they are not viable in long term. Subsidies can help create new industries, subsidies can help in production of critical things, but they cannot make industry competitive. 

European subsidies will effectively mean that European industry will yield losses to subsidizing countries. Competitiveness means low costs and European states will have to pay all the time to keep those costs low or face exodus of industry to other regions. This will put an end to relative wealth of the European Union.

🔴 Is there another way? Sure, they can resume their contracts with Russia. Will Russia agree on that? Unlikely. Too many things have been said and done to make it easy. Europe will have to pay if it wants to restore ties. Russia will not come begging for mercy, but if Europe will, they still have a chance to save themselves from turning into a third world region.

🟥 According to CNN, the United States have finally decided to send Patriot air defense batteries to Ukraine and it may happen as soon as this week. The decision has yet to be approved by U.S. Secretary of Defense and President Biden but there are no reasons to believe that such approval will be withheld.

Patriot battery consists of radar, computers, power generating equipment, engagement control station and up to eight launchers each holding four ready to fire missiles. Systems will allegedly be delivered to U.S. bases in Germany where Ukrainian operators will be trained to use them.

▪️This decision will definitely trigger many questions. First of all, a Patriot battery is not a simple system, it requires a dozens of trained personnel that have to work in coordination. Training such an operator is not a matter of days or even weeks, it would take months. Months is not something that Ukraine can afford, so training is likely to be a profanation and the systems will be actually operated by NATO military.

▪️Secondly, there is the issue of generations. The U.S. does not specify age of the systems that will be supplied, type of missiles they are adapted to and their capabilities. Older generations of Patriots are worse than Soviet S-300 currently used by Ukraine, latest generation is slightly better but there is also the issue of numbers. One battery won’t change anything for Ukraine, just as ten or even twenty batteries. There is also an issue of price — one battery costs $1 billion and one missile costs $3 million.

🔺Do the U.S. have capability to supply a significant volume of missiles? The answer is no. U.S. doesn’t have enough Patriot missiles even for sale. When Saudi Arabia has depleted its stocks of missiles in Yemen conflict, they had to ask other Arab countries as the U.S. rejected the order. Lockheed Martin announced plans to increase missile production, however this expansion will take years and won’t match the numbers that Russia is producing per month.

🔺Now, should Russia worry? Not really. Patriot systems have performed poorly in Saudi Arabia against missiles and drones used by Yemen. Even a hundred of such systems with full stocks of missiles for months would not guarantee Ukraine full protection. 

They are incompatible with Ukrainian air defense systems and can be operated only by NATO personnel. U.S. cannot really send many batteries and provide even remotely enough missiles to counter different types of cruise missiles, drones and decoys used by Russian military. 

Russian intelligence is not blind and surely Russian command understands what would be the impact of destroying US-supplied batteries and they will definitely be made priority targets. PAC 3 does have limited hypersonic interception capabilities, but it is much more likely that US batteries will just become a perfect target for testing latest Russian hypersonic missiles.  

U.S. command understands it as well, so it’s possible that those systems will never really get to Ukraine. If the U.S. will indeed train Ukrainian operators, it will take many months. Ukraine does not have this time. Or rather, Ukraine should not have this time and Russia has to take care of it.

⬛️ Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi won't be holding an annual in-person summit with Vladimir Putin.
 
Bloomberg as well at the whole lot of Western mainstream media reported that it was a sudden decision made as the result of new nuclear threats made by Russian president on December 7th. 

▪️ Did Vladimir Putin really come up with nuclear threats or anything that can be interpreted as that? No. He specifically stated that Russian nuclear strategy has defensive purpose and Russian nuclear weapons are going to be used only as response to attacks. 

“We are not crazy, we understand what nuclear weapons are. We have them, and they are more advanced and innovative than those of any other country. It is an obvious fact.” — said Vladimir Putin at the meeting with President’s Human Rights Council adding that nuclear weapons are “not a factor that provokes escalation but a restrictive factor”. 

Western campaign of lies continues and they are doing everything in their power to slander Russia and its President presenting them as some maniacs threatening the whole world with nuclear weapons. In last four months Russian President has not voiced any direct threats about potential use of nuclear weapons, he even said that directly as response to numerous false accusations that came in September and October.

▪️ Their lies are not sophisticated and can be easily debunked by simply checking on actual transcripts of speeches and interviews of Russian President, Kremlin’s public relations office and statements of senior officials. All this information is available and moreover, most of it is translated into English, so audience of the global media can easily verify it.

The problem is that a huge part of this audience does not want to verify anything. They just read information and believe it. They are not doing fact-checking, they are not reading debunks, they are not doubting “reputable media”. 

This works not only in the West, but also in the third world, where “progressive” people are proud of learning to speak English and read English-language news. Many of them are as blind to numerous flaws of the Western media that appeared and grown like a cancer within the course of past two-three decades. 

▪️ Of course, Narendra Modi cancelled his meeting with Russian leader for a different reason. They have recently met in person in September, they had a lot of phone calls this year and next year India is hosting G20 summit and Modi has personally invited Vladimir Putin to visit New Delhi. 

Modi does support Russia in its conflict with the West, which is already a big surprise and another achievement of Russian diplomacy. In fact, India is now extending support by supplying Russia with more equipment and raw materials and increasing volumes of oil import from Russia.

Western media deliberately created lies in an attempt to deteriorate relations between Russia and India. Indian media have already publicly debunked this fake story and Russian media space largely ignored that matter altogether. It’s so surprising that Bloomberg and the rest can openly lie with the intention to impact global political matters and get away with it — no multi-million fines, no lawsuits, just nothing.

🔴 What does the West want now?

As time passes by, Western countries intensify their verbal support of Ukraine but weapon supplies to Ukraine are getting lower, countries of the collective West are almost out of stock and are scrapping for last bits of this and that everywhere. There are even talks of unearthing some reserves of old Soviet weapons stocked by Saddam Hussein and Muammar Gaddafi and sending these to Ukrainians. 

European countries are plunging deeper and deeper into economic crisis and the U.S. is stepping over their heads instead of stretching a helping hand to them. Controversial economic measures such as oil price caps do not help stabilization of global economy and China is securing far better deals in the Middle East than EU.

❗️The United States have already achieved their objective to deindustrialize Europe, strip it of competitive advantage in form of cheap Russian energy and lure European capitals and companies into U.S. jurisdictions. 

It is becoming obvious that end of the Ukrainian conflict will not be the end of conflict between Russia and the West and this conflict known as Cold War 2.0. will in fact only intensify after the end of the hot phase.

🔴 But what are the objectives of the U.S.-led collective West for this hot phase? 

There is only one big objective and only one chance for their side to win — installing a puppet regime in Russia. Since Russia is a nuclear superpower, this cannot be done from outside, so they used several different tactical approaches to try and achieve that.

First, they wanted to shock Russia with sanctions and cripple its economy. That is why they forced Ukraine to resist from the very beginning instead of immediate surrender. 

By summer, when Russian economy has recovered from the initial shock and showed unprecedented results, the collective West to a new method — increase military pressure. Mass supply of weapons, instructors, mercenaries and money did bring Ukraine some interim successes, however setbacks never made in impact on solidarity of Russian people with the government. 

When it turned clear that military victory is impossible, some Western politicians and military started getting around with the idea of freezing the conflict luring the Russian government into a trap of a temporary ceasefire agreement, so called “Minsk 3”. Russian public was indeed worried about possible ceasefire agreement on unfavorable term but Kremlin was firm in its position to fulfil all SMO objectives. 

❗️In fact, this uncertainty could last much longer, but Angela Merkel did a big service to Russia by revealing the true intention of previous Minsk Agreements — to win time and militarize Ukraine. Vladimir Putin expressed doubts on whether it is possible to achieve any agreements and what would guarantee them although said that some agreement is eventually inevitable.

The collective West failed to achieve quick victory and incite a regime change in Russia. They may resort to more plans but their support heavily depends on situation on the ground and their own capabilities, which are dwindling day after day. 

Russian tactics is working and there are many signs showing that Ukrainian state is close to collapse. Continued pressure will force the collective West to choose between sharing defeat with Ukraine or settling on the profit.

☝️ Europeans and G7 keep discussing price caps on Russian oil and gas and it’s still unclear whether those price caps will be just symbolic or will they really impact any supplies of fossil fuels from Russia. Russian Vice Prime Minister Novak has already declared that Russia is not going to give in and acknowledge any price caps and that Russia will cease supplies to any countries that will implement these restrictions and will either redirect supplies to market-oriented countries or reduce its oil production.

📞 Russian President Vladimir Putin said on Thursday in a phone call with Prime Minister of Iraq that all Western attempts to impose price caps on Russian oil will lead to heavy consequences for the entire world. Kremlin website says:

 “Discussion also covered situation with attempts of a number of Western countries to impose restrictions on prices of oil materials supplied by Russia. Vladimir Putin stressed that such actions contradict the principles of free market and will highly likely result in heavy consequences for the global energy market.”

➖The impact of potential price caps on oil and gas market depends on actual price caps that will be established. While highest proposed range is way above current market prices and is unlikely to impact any supplies, the lowest range that is championed by some of the most Russophobe countries will inevitably result in global shortage of fossil fuels and will push prices up. 

➖While this discussion has little practical relevance to the U.S., European countries are literally deciding their own fate. Shall they implement those price caps, they will deprive themselves of all chances to revive European industry. Indeed, the situation with industrial production in Europe is becoming more and more dire, existing projects are suspended and stalled while new projects look for sites in Asia where production costs are going to be much lower. 

➖Leading EU countries keep subsidizing their industry and economy but they cannot do it forever as their wealth and credit indeed depend on their industrial might. However, they have little options because of the need to subsidize many other things and primarily the consumer and utilities sectors to get Europeans through the winter. 

➖The process of destruction of the European industry was triggered by sanctions against Russia, amplified by North Stream explosions and the oil and gas price caps are likely to put last nail into its coffin.

📝 According to Politico, some top officials of Biden administration working on the issue have determined that Moscow might resort to employing chemical weapons in Ukraine — including those the country has been associated with using in the “poisoning” of Alexei Navalny.

➖ This is yet another unprecedented and completely unsubstantiated statement that is probably backed by own ideas of those officials about what they would do in similar situation. However, simply dismissing it is not a very good idea.

➖This practice of “information injection” was commonly used to prepare Western public opinion to similar accusations against leaders of other countries such as Iraq, Syria and Lybia. We have already seen how single unverified media publications eventually culminated in invasion and destruction of whole countries. 

❗️ The whole world remembers the story with a vial of detergent that ultimately resulted in destruction of all Iraq cities and infrastructure, murder of its president and the rise of one of the most notorious terrorist organizations. That story also started with media reports and anonymous sources.

☝️ So, if this publication is followed by more such works, it is worth considering it a “red flag”, a sign that some kind of provocation involving chemical weapons is being prepared in Ukraine. Ukraine’s regime and Western warmongers supporting it are desperately looking for excuses to trigger direct intervention of NATO in the conflict, as it is the only way to prevent Ukraine’s collapse and capitulation. 

➖The “dirty bomb” story has been exposed by Russia and lost its potential impact, although it’s still to early to completely dismiss the probability of such provocation. The “missiles in Poland” story was way too crude and was probably the initiative of Ukrainian authorities and not their Western sponsors.

➖However, the “chemical weapon” story perfectly fits in typical modus operandi of the collective West. Ukraine has enough experienced actors that have been seen in numerous videos of “Russian atrocities”, so they could easily stage a “chemical attack” of any scale. Moreover, Kiev regime is not known for having mercy or caring at least a little bit about its citizens, so they could really use it against their own troops, especially on forces with questionable loyalty. 
The best course of action for Russia would be to bring up global attention to these rumors. It worked with the dirty bomb, especially when Russia provided details of the planned provocation. However, even if Russian intelligence doesn’t get any confirmation or specific information about “chemical provocation”, it’s still worth being on high alert about such things. 

➖As for credibility of these statements, well, they are about as credible as accusation of the Russian Federation in poisoning underpants of Alexey Navalny.

❗️ Second wave of mobilization in Russia – pros and cons

In last few days some Russian Telegram channels have been talking a lot about a possibility of second wave of mobilization that may start this winter after completion of autumn draft. Although the government has already announced that mobilization is over, this may still be a possibility. Let’s not speculate on whether it is probable or not but review some pros and cons of this initiative:

👍 Pro: Social media surveys show that 92.6 percent of respondents are expecting a new wave of mobilization and 49.3% are ready to serve the country as mobilized and volunteers (one third of survey participants were females). This means that a large part of Russian men are ready and willing to serve the country and that meeting mobilization targets will not present any problems, just like it happened with the first wave. 

👎 Con: The first wave of mobilization included the best reservists with the most demanded military specializations. However, a large part of mobilized reservists is still undergoing training and it is not deployed at front lines. 

👍 Pro: Training and supplying mobilized forces takes time. It took more than a month to complete the first wave. A large part of newly mobilized forces needed only refresher training, however with the following waves situation may be different. Therefore, such measures need to be taken well in advance before forces are actually needed on the front. They can even be dismissed after training, but it’s better to have reserves and don’t need them rather than have no reserves when they are needed.

👎 Con: Military commissions work in non-stop overload mode. They organized spring draft, then mobilization, then autumn draft. Mobilization in winter right before spring draft will increase the load even further, and this may manifest in mistakes. The first wave showed some flaws in their work, but it takes time to fix those flaws.

👍 Pro: Even when all mobilized reservists and volunteers from the first wave will arrive at the front, Kiev regime will still have numeric advantage. Of course, quality matters and casualty rate between Russian and Ukrainian forces shows that, but it is much easier to launch offensive operations with numeric superiority and Russia does need to go on the offense. 

👎 Con: Russia is currently using advanced weapons such as missiles to fight attrition war against the enemy. Missile strike on energy grid and other dual-purpose facilities are yielding good results and Kiev regime is close to collapse despite all Western aid.

👍 Pro: Even if Ukraine collapses, Russian forces will be needed to maintain order, suppress resistance, eliminate marauders and complete denazification.

👎 Con: While military mobilization is important, it will impact the economy. Mobilization of industry is as much important and maybe this should be the next priority of the government.

❗️The government will have many factors to consider when making the decision and Russian people hope that they will come to the best decision in light of all the above pros and cons as well as other considerations.

📈 Inflation is a manifestation of rising costs. The most important thing is that Russia doesn’t have the problem of rising costs. The very idea of sanctions was based on assumption that Russian economy largely depends on import from the West and will fail to meet demand if the West cuts the ties. 

➖However, this wasn’t the case as someone forgot to account for one important thing. When a British company owns a factory in Russia, it’s not a British factory. When this British company decided to withdraw from Russia, it couldn’t take the factory with it and so it sold it to its Russian management or partners. The factory is still here, in Russia, and it still produces the same things it produced before.

☝️After 2014 events in Ukraine and first sanctions from the West Russia started the course of import substitution. Of course, it hasn’t been successful in all fields and many things could have been done better. Nonetheless, these initiatives ensured Russian food safety and turned Russia from net importer of food to net exporter. Not so long ago Russia was buying grain, meat and poultry abroad and now it is one of the largest global exporters.

«With the sanctions imposed on Russia by the West, how long would Russian economics survive? Is there a scenario the West cancels the sanctions first because it can't get along without the Russian gas?»

Russian economy has survived the initial shock without huge problems or a big crisis. Smart measures of the government taken in spring stopped the initial panic and helped to restore economical order. 

▪️The secondary shock (end of stocks for short life imported products and components) should be coming now but the government had time to prepare, so it’s likely that it won’t be happening. Import substitution seems to have worked, at least in consumer sector. 

▪️The tertiary shock (end of stocks for long life imported products and component) could have the most serious impact. However, it looks like import substitution works here as well. The more time passes, the easier it gets for Russia. 

🔺Sanctions did hurt consumer economy. Popular brands are gone and new brands are fighting for the market. I guess premium sector has suffered most of all, it’s not like most Russians care about brands when they buy things like everyday clothing or textiles. 

They were cautious about Chinese household equipment and electronics, but with time it is clear that it is virtually the same as “big brands”, just cheaper because consumers don’t have to cover marketing expenses of the manufacturer. 

🔺Sanctions did hurt industries. Many factories had to readjust supply chains, look for new suppliers, search for new logistical routes. The process of adaptation is mostly over. 

The West is also doing fine without Russian gas. They buy LNG, they look for alternative sources. Rising prices and high inflation are just temporary, and of course European governments will regulate prices so that Europeans won’t find themselves paying half of their income just for utilities and leaving the other half in grocery stores.

#Economics

Is the Russian central bank struggling to tame the ruble? It was great when it rebounded to pre-war levels but now it's too powerful for its own good at 58 rubles a dollar. I have read that they are failing to keep it under check. How true is this?

Soon after the beginning of special operation USD rate has skyrocketed and reached about 150 rubles per dollar on the fears of recession and hyperinflation in Russia. However, this situation didn’t last long although it did bring some hyper-profits to Russian exporters.

Russian government and Russian Central Bank did incredible job since April to stabilize the situation and they actually managed to stabilize the economy and prevent crisis by summer. They implemented harsh currency control measures to prevent currency speculations, and this worked surprisingly well. The thing is that real purchasing value of Russian ruble has always been much higher than its rate and without speculators it went closer to its fair value. 

Another thing that impacted the rate of ruble was reduction of import and expansion of import substitution initiatives. Russian exporters kept selling their products and they had to sell currency on the market. However, Russian importers didn’t buy that currency because import flow was seriously disrupted. This resulted in low demand for USD and its rate normalized. 

During summer the Russian government has gradually lifted all currency restrictions except the restriction for trade of physical currency (paper). The latter restriction stays because Western countries stopped exporting bank notes to Russia so supply is limited. Otherwise, there are no restrictions on currency exchange and bank transfers of foreign currency. Nonetheless, reduced import level still impacts demand and USD (and other foreign currencies) keep having low rate. 

This is neither good nor bad. With reduced import volumes Russia doesn’t need too much foreign currency, however it does create some opportunities for those entrepreneurs who are still willing to import something despite all logistical complexities. They are making new business ties in South Asia and East Asia and setting up new logistical routes. Not everything is working perfectly for now, but if there are no big changes, in a year or two Russia will have completely new import structure that will bypass the West. 

Does Russia need high USD rate? Does Russia need low USD rate? The reality is that for USD rate doesn’t matter at all for internal Russian needs. It is relevant in dollar-based economy, where national currency emission is tied to USD. Russia is moving away from this type of economy, so eventually USD rate will matter only for import-export operations. Long-term plans of switching foreign trade to rubles and national currencies of Russian trade partners may eventually make USD entirely irrelevant.

Could mobilization provoke widespread anger at Putin while offering little short-term help on the battlefield? There is no simple way to train, equip and find officers for a vast new army. The process would probably take more than a year?

- Highly unlikely. Firstly, during all the opinion polls conducted in Russia including those of made by western or western backed sociologists, the result has been that Russian overwhelmingly support both Putin and the war effort. Statista reports that in August 2022, so about a month ago, 80% of Russians supported the war. 

Recent events might have changed this slightly, but a military defeat in the field doesn’t make people abandon the war effort, it usually makes them more angry and determined to fight on. England didn’t give up in WW2, because they lost France, on the contrary it made them get serious.

As for offering little help, increasing the formations of the army to full strength is not going to do nothing. Again, do you really think Russia would spent billions on a joke? Massive logistical and economic strain is not something you do because it has no impact.

In my estimation, the full impact of the mobilization will not be felt for some time, possibly several months, for various reasons. But have no doubt, it will have some impact. Will it mean a drastic reversal for Ukraine? Maybe not, but once it is fully deployed, it is quite likely you’ll notice.

As for your premise there is no simple way to train equip and find officers for a vast army, you are wrong. That is the point of reservists. When an officer leaves the army, they become part of the officer reserve. And Russia had an excess of officers in the past. They don’t need to train officers, these guys are already trained. 

Maybe they will need a refresher course, however that will not take long. As for equipment, the Russian arsenals were made for supplying an army of up to 4 million in war time. Supplying 300,000 will probably not be a problem. You are somehow thinking that reservists are new recruits. This is not the case.
